Trim and discard the root and the dark green leafy part from the @leek{1}. Halve lengthways, then thinly slice widthways.

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2}(peeled) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Pour the @water{750%ml} for the stock into a #medium saucepan{} on high heat. Add the @vegetable stock paste{20%g}, stir to combine. Bring to the boil then reduce the heat to the lowest setting.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a #large frying pan{} on medium heat.

Once hot, add the leek and fry until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}. Stir occasionally.

Stir in the garlic and @tomato puree{30%g} (and a drizzle more oil if it's a bit dry). Stir and cook for ~{1%minute}.

Add the @risotto rice{175%g}, stir and cook for ~{1%minute} until the edges of the rice are translucent, then add the @cider vinegar{15%n%ml} and allow it to evaporate, ~{30%seconds}.

Stir a ladle of stock into the rice pan. When the stock has been absorbed by the rice, stir in another ladle of stock.

Keep the pan on medium heat and continue stirring in stock, letting it absorb each time.

The cooking time should be ~{20-25%minutes}. Your risotto is done when your rice is 'al dente' - cooked through but with a tiny bit of firmness left in the middle.

When the risotto has almost 6 mins left, drain the @king prawns{300%g} and pat dry with #kitchen paper{}.

Stir the prawns into the risotto and simmer until cooked, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns. They're cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Once cooked, remove your risotto from the heat and add the @grated hard Italian style cheese{20%g} and a knob of @?butter{knob}.

Stir vigorously until the cheese and butter have melted. Taste and add @?salt{} and @?pepper{} if needed.

Serve your prawn and tomato risotto in #bowls{} with the @chilli flakes{1}(sprinkled on top) (add less if you'd prefer things milder).

Enjoy!